			        <p>Write your character's story here.  You can go into as much detail as you want; this box will scroll.  You can also add images using floats to accentuate the story.</p>
			        <p>Here's an example of an image set to float to the right of the text.  The text will flow around the image, and once it is past the height of the image, will return to taking up the full width of the div.</p>
			        <p>Just remember to include a padding class (like the example p-3 class) to ensure the text doesn't just crash into the image itself, keeping a bit of extra space between the text and the image.  It just looks better.</p>
			        <p>You can also float the image to the right instead, whichever is your preference.  I personally recommend any images alternate between right and left for visual appeal.</p>
			    </div>
			    
			    <div class="card bg-faded p-2 pb-3 mb-0 text-uppercase" style="text-align:right;border:none;border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.25)">
			        <h2>Section 2 Title</h2>
			    </div>
			    <div class="p-1 text-justify mb-3">
			        <img class="float-left p-3" src="https://placehold.co/145x200">
			        <p>Here's another text box, this time with the title aligned to the right and the image floating to the left.  Notice how there's more visual distinction by mirroring which way the alignment goes?</p>
			        <p>When adding a new section, make sure that the text div includes a bottom margin class (such as mb-3) to keep the sections from smashing together!  Remember, negative space in text is a good thing because it gives the reader's eyes room to read!  It's much easier to read text that isn't all crunched up against other elements than it is to try to read one jumbled brick!</p>
